Implementing MLP¶

In this notebook, we are going to use the mfcc extracted features as an input for the Multi-layer Perceptron classifier (MLP)

Model definition¶

For our MLP, we are going to use the mfcc features as input, with shape (40, 173).
We start by defining a sequential model where we add 4 hidden layers and the filters number start at 1024 and decreases by half everytime the data go to the next layer. These layers use 'relu' as the activation function.
Then we add BatchNormalization(), a function that normalizes the output of the previous layer for each mini-batch to make the training faster and more stable.
To prevent overfitting, we procede to use Dropout() by dropping some features with 30% chance.
At the end, we added a flattening layer to moldure the output shape we need and a final output layer with a number of neurons equal to num_classes and using the 'softmax' activation function.

In [11]:
def create_model(input_shape, num_classes):
    model = Sequential()
    
    # 1st hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(1024, activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    
    # 2nd hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    # 3rd hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    
    # 4th hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    

    # Output layer with softmax activation
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

    return model
In [13]:
fold_n = 1 # Starting fold
num_epochs = 20
all_folds_history = [] # Keeps all accuracy and loss values for each epoch to help 
confusion_matrices = [] # Keeps all the confusion matrices
fold_accuracies = [] # Keeps all the accuracies of each fold
for train, test in kfold.split(X, y):
    
    model = create_model(input_shape, num_classes)
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary() # Shows a summary of the model built
    
    print("Shape of X[train]:", X[train].shape)
    print("Shape of y[train]:", y[train].shape)

    # Train the model
    print(f'Training for fold {fold_n} ...')

    # Train the model and save the history
    history = model.fit(X[train], y[train], epochs=num_epochs, batch_size=32)
    all_folds_history.append(history)
    temp_accuracy = history.history['accuracy'][-1]
    fold_accuracies.append(temp_accuracy)

    # Evaluate the model
    scores = model.evaluate(X[test], y[test], verbose=0)
    print(f'Score for fold {fold_n}: loss of {scores[0]}; accuracy of {scores[1]*100}%')
    
    # Builds the confusion matrix of the model
    predictions = model.predict(X[test])
    predicted_classes = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    true_classes = np.argmax(y[test], axis=1)
    cm = confusion_matrix(true_classes, predicted_classes)
    confusion_matrices.append(cm)
    
    del model
    
    fold_n += 1

Performance evaluation¶

In [15]:
# Builds a graphical version of the confusion matrix
def build_cm(cm, title, cmap):
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.ylabel('True Label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [16]:
# Plotting the accuracy and loss functions
def build_stats(history, epochs_range, i):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))  
    
    # Building accuracy graphic
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, history.history['accuracy'], label='Training Accuracy', color = 'green')
    plt.title(f'Fold {i+1} - Training Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    
    # Building loss graphic
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(epochs_range, history.history['loss'], label='Training Loss', color = 'red')
    plt.title(f'Fold {i+1} - Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    
    # Display the plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
